The Golden Manifest is the canonical, immutable, cryptographically trusted identity record of a model.
It is the one true description of what that model is allowed to be ‚Äî its form, its parameters, its legitimate soul.

If the model you are about to run does not match its Golden Manifest exactly, then by definition:
	‚Ä¢	the model has been tampered with
	‚Ä¢	or replaced
	‚Ä¢	or corrupted
	‚Ä¢	or trojaned
	‚Ä¢	or swapped
	‚Ä¢	or altered in memory or on disk
	‚Ä¢	or its supply chain has been compromised

And Hades must quarantine it immediately.

Let‚Äôs break it down clearly.

‚∏ª

üü© THE GOLDEN MANIFEST

Pantheon-Prime‚Äôs definitive identity registry for models

The Golden Manifest is a JSON (or TOML/YAML) record generated only once:

At the moment a model is accepted as ‚Äútrusted and legitimate‚Äù by Pantheon.

It is then frozen forever ‚Äî cryptographically sealed.

This manifest lives under:

pantheon_core/registry/models/<model_id>.json

It contains four essential classes of data:

‚∏ª

1. Structural Identity (Architecture Hash)

The architecture is hashed as:

arch_hash = SHA256(architecture_bytes)

This covers things like:
	‚Ä¢	graph structure
	‚Ä¢	module layout
	‚Ä¢	computation graph IR
	‚Ä¢	safetensors metadata
	‚Ä¢	layer ordering
	‚Ä¢	shapes & types minus the raw numerical weights

This ensures the model structure cannot be replaced (e.g., with a malicious ONNX file or altered TorchScript graph).

‚∏ª

2. Parameter Identity (Weights Hash)

The raw tensor bytes (just the numbers) are hashed as:

param_hash = SHA256(parameter_bytes)

This ensures the exact numerical weights haven‚Äôt been:
	‚Ä¢	modified
	‚Ä¢	truncated
	‚Ä¢	poisoned
	‚Ä¢	swapped
	‚Ä¢	quantized differently
	‚Ä¢	altered via supply-chain attack
	‚Ä¢	replaced with trojaned tensors

Even changing a single float in layer 47 changes the hash.

This is the ‚Äúsoul‚Äù of the model.

‚∏ª

3. Provenance Metadata

This includes:
	‚Ä¢	model name
	‚Ä¢	version
	‚Ä¢	source (owner, lab, repo URL)
	‚Ä¢	creation date, operator identity
	‚Ä¢	serialization format (must be safetensors/TS/ONNX)

This stops:
	‚Ä¢	pickle-based execution payloads
	‚Ä¢	cloned model substitution attacks
	‚Ä¢	tampering with upstream providers

‚∏ª

4. Operational State

Includes:
	‚Ä¢	status = {ACTIVE, BLOCKED, QUARANTINED}
	‚Ä¢	last_verified_at
	‚Ä¢	last_verified_by
	‚Ä¢	notes / audit history pointer

This ties Hades, Blacksmith, and MotherDuck together into the forensic chain.

‚∏ª

üü® Why It‚Äôs Called ‚ÄúGolden‚Äù

It is:
	‚Ä¢	the reference
	‚Ä¢	the truth-source
	‚Ä¢	the canonical identity
	‚Ä¢	the one file against which all future instances of that model are verified

It‚Äôs ‚Äúgolden‚Äù in the same sense as:
	‚Ä¢	a golden master disc
	‚Ä¢	a golden firmware image
	‚Ä¢	a golden PKI certificate
	‚Ä¢	a golden reference genome

It is the uncorrupted ideal.

‚∏ª

üü• Why It Must Never Change

Once created, the Golden Manifest is immutable.

If you update the model:
	‚Ä¢	new weights
	‚Ä¢	new architecture
	‚Ä¢	new retraining
	‚Ä¢	new distillation

You do not modify the manifest.

You create a new model_id and register a new Golden Manifest.

This prevents attackers from:
	‚Ä¢	overwriting the manifest to match their tampered model
	‚Ä¢	updating the hash silently
	‚Ä¢	forging backward compatibility

The manifest represents a promised state.
Breaking that promise = quarantine.

‚∏ª

üü¶ Example of a Golden Manifest

{
  "model_id": "gpt_squire_3.1",
  "name": "GPT-Squire",
  "owner": "Pantheon-Lab",
  "version": "3.1",
